\par \hich\af44\dbch\af31505\loch\f44 \hich\f44  There are 10 distinct symbols, 0, 1, 2, \'85\loch\f44 ,9.
\par 
\par \hich\af44\dbch\af31505\loch\f44       Computers use base 2 (binary) system. There are only 0 and 1.These two binary digits are commonly referred to as bits.}{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af44\afs36 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f44\insrsid11017018\charrsid13244520 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af44\afs36 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f44\ul\insrsid11017018\charrsid13244520 \hich\af44\dbch\af31505\loch\f44 Conversion of decimal to binary:
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af44\afs36 \ltrch\fcs0 \f44\cf1\insrsid11017018\charrsid13244520 \hich\af44\dbch\af31505\loch\f44   Step1: Divide the decimal number by 2 repeatedly
\par \hich\af44\dbch\af31505\loch\f44   Step2: Keep track of the remainders
\par \hich\af44\dbch\af31505\loch\f44   Step3: Continue this process until the quotient 
\par \hich\af44\dbch\af31505\loch\f44              becomes zero
\par \hich\af44\dbch\af31505\loch\f44   Step4: Write the remainders in reverse order to
\par \hich\af44\dbch\af31505\loch\f44             obtain The binary number
\par 
\par }\pard \ltrpar\ql \li0\ri0\nowidctlpar\wrapdefault\faauto\rin0\lin0\itap0 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af44\afs40 \ltrch\fcs0 \f44\fs24\insrsid11017018\charrsid13244520 \hich\af44\dbch\af31505\loch\f44 Ex. Convert 25}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af44\afs26 \ltrch\fcs0 
