\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0\afs40 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f0\fs24\insrsid11017018\charrsid13244520 \hich\af0\dbch\af31505\loch\f0 1) }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0\afs40 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f0\fs24\ul\insrsid11017018\charrsid13244520 \hich\af0\dbch\af31505\loch\f0 
Ternary (or) Conditional operator :
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs40 \ltrch\fcs0 \f0\fs24\insrsid11017018\charrsid13244520 \hich\af0\dbch\af31505\loch\f0        A ternary operator pair  " ? "  and " :  " is available in C language. It is used to construct a conditional expression.
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af31505\loch\f0      The general form of ternar\hich\af0\dbch\af31505\loch\f0 y operator is  :
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af31505\loch\f0         Exp1  ?  Exp2  :  Exp3 ;
\par 
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af31505\loch\f0     In this operator first Exp1 is evaluated, if it is true then Exp2 is evaluated and its value becomes the value of the Expression, otherwise Exp3 is evaluated and its value becomes the value of the Expr
\hich\af0\dbch\af31505\loch\f0 ession.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0\afs40 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f0\fs24\ul\insrsid11017018\charrsid13244520 \hich\af0\dbch\af31505\loch\f0 Eg : 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs40 \ltrch\fcs0 \f0\fs24\insrsid11017018\charrsid13244520 \hich\af0\dbch\af31505\loch\f0    int a=10,b=20,c;
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af31505\loch\f0    c = a<b? a : b;
\par \hich\af0\dbch\af31505\loch\f0 output will be  c =10
\par 
\par 
\par 
\par 
\par 
\par 
\par 
\par 
\par 
